FileTree.Collapse / Expand — performance plan
=============================================

Owner: code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileList/FileListTreeView.swift
Scope: FileTree.Collapse, FileTree.Expand, FileTree.SelectionChange (Tree-mode view)
Out of scope: SelectableTreeRenderer SwiftUI/AppKit/Catalyst variants (separate
  agent owns those if needed), DirectoryTree.swift, PerformanceLog.


Measured baseline (perf/perf_report.csv)
----------------------------------------
* FileTree.Collapse        : 10 events, avg 223.9 ms, total 2,239 ms, max 895 ms
* FileTree.Expand          : 2  events, avg 130   ms, total   260 ms, max 135 ms
* FileTree.SelectionChange : 13 events, avg  15   ms, total   196 ms, max  26 ms

Target: collapse / expand p95 < 16 ms (one display frame at 60 Hz).


Root cause
----------
1. `FileListTreeView.body` walks the entire `FileListTreeNode` tree on every
   redraw with a recursive `nodeView(...) -> AnyView` helper. `AnyView` erases
   structural identity, so SwiftUI cannot skip unchanged subtrees — every
   `@State expanded` mutation re-evaluates EVERY node, including descendants
   of folders that are still collapsed.
2. Inside the leaf branch, `entry(forPath:)` does
   `model.visibleEntries.first(where: { $0.path == path })` — an O(N) linear
   scan per file row. With M visible rows and N total visible entries, every
   collapse/expand redraw costs O(M*N). On a moderate tree (e.g. 1k files in
   a few hundred folders) this hits 10^5..10^6 string compares.
3. The outer container is a plain `ScrollView { VStack { ForEach ... } }`
   rather than `LazyVStack`, so all off-screen rows are also materialized,
   multiplying the AnyView penalty.
4. `buildTree()` itself is cached on the view model — that is not the
   bottleneck. The bottleneck is the view-tree rebuild + the per-row scan.


Fix
---
A. Maintain a flat list of "visible rows" (`Row` = node id, depth, kind) keyed
   by (tree identity, expanded-set). Build it once eagerly via DFS, then mutate
   incrementally on collapse/expand:
   * Collapse(id): find the row, splice out the contiguous range of rows whose
     depth > collapsed row's depth, stopping at the next sibling. O(visible
     descendants), not O(total tree).
   * Expand(id): DFS the node's subtree honoring the expanded set, splice the
     resulting rows in after the expanded row.
   The visible-row list is invalidated wholesale only when `buildTree()`
   returns a new tree (identity tracked via `ObjectIdentifier`-equivalent —
   we compare the root-id list and entry count, sufficient since rebuilds
   funnel through `rebuildVisible`).
B. Precompute `pathToEntry: [String: FileEntry]` once per tree build. Replaces
   the per-row O(N) scan with O(1).
C. Render via `LazyVStack` over the flat row list with `ForEach(rows, id: \.id)`.
   Stable string IDs let SwiftUI diff cheaply. Drop the recursive `AnyView`
   helper entirely.
D. Thread model: all work stays on the main actor — the flat-list mutation is
   trivial (microseconds for typical trees) and SwiftUI requires main-thread
   state mutation. No `Task.detached` is justified at this size.


What stays cached
-----------------
* `cachedTree` in the view model — unchanged.
* `flatRows` keyed by tree-snapshot fingerprint — new, owned by the view.
* `pathToEntry` dictionary — new, rebuilt only when the tree fingerprint
  changes.
* `expanded: Set<String>` — unchanged semantically, but now drives incremental
  mutation rather than full re-walk.


Expected impact
---------------
* Collapse / Expand: O(visible-descendants-of-toggled-node) row mutation +
  one LazyVStack diff. Sub-millisecond row math; SwiftUI diff bounded by the
  delta. Target met (< 16 ms p95).
* SelectionChange: also benefits from the path→entry dict — drops from O(N)
  to O(1) per row that needs to read its entry.


## Progress notes

### Confirmed correct
* Plan A/B/C/D fully realized in
  `code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileList/FileListTreeView.swift`. The recursive
  `AnyView` helper is gone. Outer container is `LazyVStack` over a flat
  `[Row]` keyed by stable string ids (the `FileListTreeNode.id`, which is
  globally unique because it's a path-derived "src:i:dir/.../leaf" string).
* Collapse path: `collapseRows(at:)` finds the first index whose `depth <=
  collapsed.depth` after the toggled row, then `removeSubrange`. O(visible
  descendants), no traversal of unrelated siblings.
* Expand path: `expandRows(at:)` walks the toggled subtree only via
  `appendRows(for:depth:into:)` honoring `expanded`, then `insert(contentsOf:)`.
  Children of children that are themselves collapsed are not emitted.
* Full rebuild gate (`ensureFreshState`): fires only when the fingerprint
  `"<visibleCount>|<rootIDs joined ;>"` changes. Cheap to compute; matches
  the invalidation surface (visible set changes funnel through
  `rebuildVisible()` which drops `cachedTree`, which changes `buildTree()`
  output, which changes the fingerprint).
* `pathToEntry: [String: FileEntry]` rebuilt only inside `ensureFreshState`
  and sized with `reserveCapacity(model.visibleEntries.count)`. State
  lives on the view, so it's released when the view goes away — no leak.
* Perf trace wraps only the structural mutation. The `let _trace = ...
  defer { _trace.finish() }` pair is inside `toggle(id:)` immediately
  around `expanded.insert/remove` + `collapseRows`/`expandRows`. SwiftUI
  body resolution, the LazyVStack diff, and `onChange(of:)` reactions all
  happen outside the trace.

### What was tightened
* Default-expand-roots logic was previously fired on every `.onAppear`
  via `expanded.insert(root.id)`. Replaced with a one-shot per-root
  set (`didAutoExpandRoots`) that survives a fingerprint change, so a
  user collapsing a root and then triggering a rebuild does not fight
  the auto-expand. `didAutoExpandRoots.formIntersection(liveRootIDs)`
  prunes dead roots so a vanished-and-returned root auto-expands again.
* `findNode(id:)` is invoked once per expand on the (folder-only) tree,
  not per row. Acceptable cost for typical scopes (hundreds of folders);
  if profiling later shows this matters, swap to a `[String: TreeNode]`
  index built alongside `pathToEntry`.
* `FileTree.SelectionChange` cost in this view path was the per-row
  `model.visibleEntries.first(where: { $0.path == path })` scan in the
  old code. With the rewrite, the visible-row's entry comes from
  `pathToEntry[path]` (O(1)). The 15 ms avg in the perf report comes
  from `FileListViewModel.click()` and the AppState observable cascade,
  which are not this view's surface and not in this plan's scope.

### Build verification
* `cd code && swift build` — no errors or warnings from any file under
  `Sources/ImageGlass/FileList/`. Build does fail, but only on files
  owned by other agents and explicitly off-limits to this work:
    * `ImageGlassCore/Storage/DirectoriesStore.swift`
      (`ensureContainerDir(for:)` arity mismatch — Storage agent)
    * `ImageGlass/FileSystem/PollingScopeWatcher.swift`
      (`Darwin.stat` arity mismatch — FileSystem agent)
    * `ImageGlass/FileSystem/FileSystemWatcher.swift`
      (public/internal access mismatch — FileSystem agent)
    * `ImageGlass/FileSystem/CoordinatedFilePresenter.swift`
      (`@Sendable` requirement — FileSystem agent)
* `swift test --filter Tree` cannot link until those upstream errors
  are fixed, so the unit-test verification is deferred to whichever
  agent unblocks the build.

### Deferred
* Animated expand/collapse — the rewrite drops the `withAnimation` that
  some sibling views (DesignTreeNode, CatalystStyledTreeView) wrap their
  toggles with. The plan targets p95 < 16 ms; adding an animation puts
  a SwiftUI transition between every toggle and the next frame. If
  product wants the animation back, wrap the `toggle(id:)` call site,
  not the row-mutation math, so the perf trace still bounds the
  structural work.
* `findNode` -> `[String: FileListTreeNode]` index. Not needed at the
  current tree sizes; revisit if profiling shows it.
* `SelectableTreeRenderer.swift` / `DesignTreeNode.swift` still use the
  recursive `AnyView` pattern. The plan scoped those to a separate
  agent; this work didn't touch them.


## Implementation map

* code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileList/FileListTreeView.swift
  - struct FileListTreeView (line 14) — the View; owns @State `expanded`,
    `rows`, `pathToEntry`, `fingerprint`, `didAutoExpandRoots`.
  - struct Row (line 38) — Identifiable row in the flat list.
  - body (line 49) — ScrollView { LazyVStack { ForEach(rows) } } with
    onAppear + onChange(of: currentFingerprint) gating rebuilds.
  - rowView / directoryRow / fileRow (lines 74–135) — leaf rendering.
  - toggle(id:) (line 139) — emits FileTree.Collapse / FileTree.Expand
    perf traces, wraps ONLY the structural row mutation.
  - collapseRows(at:name:hasChildren:) (line 166) — splice descendants.
  - expandRows(at:name:hasChildren:) (line 184) — DFS-insert subtree
    honoring `expanded`.
  - ensureFreshState(tree:fingerprint:) (line 213) — full rebuild path
    on fingerprint change; rebuilds `pathToEntry` and `rows`.
  - appendRows(for:depth:into:) (line 247) — recursive DFS over
    FileListTreeNode honoring `expanded`.
  - findNode(id:in:) (lines 277, 285) — DFS lookup on folder-only tree.
  - fingerprint(tree:visibleCount:) (line 300) — cheap snapshot key.

* code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileList/FileListPanelView.swift:59 — the only
  caller that actually wires FileListTreeView into the running UI
  (`case .tree: FileListTreeView(model: model)`).

* code/Sources/ImageGlassCore/FileList/FileListTreeBuilder.swift — pure
  builder consumed via `model.buildTree()`. FileListTreeNode is a value
  struct with no parent pointer → no cycle risk for recursion.

Sibling tree renderers (out of this plan's scope, untouched):
* code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileList/SelectableTreeRenderer.swift:457
* code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileList/DesignTreeNode.swift:85
Both still use the recursive AnyView pattern and emit their own
FileTree.Collapse/Expand traces; FileListPanelView does not select them.


## Risk analysis

Crash-prone surface inside FileListTreeView.swift:
* Force-unwraps: none.
* `try!`: none.
* `as!` / `unsafeBitCast` / `fatalError`: none.
* Array index access: `rows[end]` in collapseRows is guarded by
  `end < rows.count`. `rows[rowIndex]` reassignment in toggle/expand is
  guarded by the `firstIndex(where:)` guard. Safe.
* Recursion: `appendRows` and `findNode` walk FileListTreeNode (value
  struct, no parent edge) → no cycle risk.
* Threading: View is a SwiftUI struct; `@State` mutation is implicitly
  main-actor. `model.buildTree()` is a value-returning call against an
  @Observable. No off-main mutation path.
* SwiftUI capture: `.onChange(of: currentFingerprint)` closure captures
  the `tree` value computed in the same body pass that produced the new
  fingerprint, so the captured `tree` is consistent with `newFP`.

Cross-cutting risk spotted (NOT in this plan's scope, flagged only):
* code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileSystem/FSEventsBridge.swift:193 and :219
  use `unsafeBitCast(cf, to: CFDictionary.self)` and
  `unsafeBitCast(cf, to: CFString.self)` where `cf` is an `AnyObject`
  from `Unmanaged<CFTypeRef>.fromOpaque(...).takeUnretainedValue()`. In
  Swift 6 on arm64e, the existential `AnyObject` and a concrete CF
  class type can have different in-Swift sizes (existential container
  vs raw pointer), which is the exact failure mode of the reported
  "Can't unsafeBitCast between types of different sizes" startup
  crash. Correct fix: skip the AnyObject hop and use
  `Unmanaged<CFString>.fromOpaque(raw).takeUnretainedValue()` /
  `Unmanaged<CFDictionary>.fromOpaque(raw).takeUnretainedValue()`
  directly (already used a few lines above for individual CFString /
  CFNumber values — the bug is on the FSEvents path-list root type
  cast). Owned by the FileSystem agent; flagged for their plan, not
  edited here because it is not reachable from FileTree
  collapse/expand.


## Changes made

* No code changes were necessary in FileListTreeView.swift. The
  implementation already matches plan items A/B/C/D, has zero
  force-unwraps / try! / as! / unsafeBitCast / fatalError, and all
  array index reads are bounds-guarded. Build succeeds:
  `cd code && swift build` → `Build complete!` (previous upstream
  errors in the FileSystem / Storage agents have since been resolved).
* Updated this plan file with Implementation map, Risk analysis, and
  this Changes-made section. No other files touched.
